\paragraph{Context}
The order star is defined on the Riemann surface $\mathcal{R}_\Phi$ for linear multistep methods, where $\Phi(w,z)$ is the characteristic polynomial of the stability matrix. The Riemann surface $\mathcal{R}_\Phi$ is defined by $\Phi(w,z)=0$. The method has order $p$ if $\Phi(e^{z},z)=O(z^{p+1})$.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\Phi$: $\Phi(w,z)$ is a polynomial function of two complex variables, $w \in W$ and $z \in Z$, with $Z=W=\mathbb{C}$; it is the characteristic polynomial $\det(wI - M(z))$ of the stability matrix of a multivalue method.
    \item $\mathcal{R}_\Phi$: the subset of $W \times Z$ defined by $\Phi(w,z)=0$; it is a Riemann surface.
    \item $p$: the order of the multivalue method, such that $\Phi(e^{z},z)=O(z^{p+1})$.
\end{itemize}
